#!/bin/sh
# postinst for send-to-influx.deb
set -e

# Only "configure" has a well-defined role for a plain, non-debhelper package
# like this one - postinst can also be invoked as abort-upgrade/abort-remove/
# abort-deconfigure/triggered, which exist to let dpkg roll back a failed
# operation or process triggers, not to (re)apply this package's own
# configuration. $2's meaning ("previously-configured version, empty only on
# a fresh install", used throughout below) specifically assumes "configure"
# too - everything in this script (user/ownership setup, debconf-driven
# configuration, the final status message) only makes sense in that context,
# so treat every other action as a clean no-op rather than risk running any
# of it on a wrong assumption about what $2 means.
if [ "$1" != "configure" ]; then
    exit 0
fi

# Point every supported Python minor at the venv's single real site-packages
# directory. Created here rather than shipped in the package - see build-deb.sh for
# why (it is what keeps dpkg from printing ~166 spurious "unable to delete old
# directory" warnings on upgrade). Must happen before anything below runs the venv.
# Idempotent: -n replaces nothing that already exists correctly, and a stale entry
# from an older layout is removed first.
# The bounds are substituted by build-deb.sh from PYTHON_MIN/MAX_SUPPORTED_MINOR,
# which also drive the Depends: range - one source of truth, so a future version bump
# cannot leave a supported interpreter without its symlink (or create one outside the
# declared range). build-deb.sh fails the build if these placeholders survive.
if [ -d /opt/send-to-influx/venv/lib/python3 ]; then
    minor=@PYTHON_MIN_SUPPORTED_MINOR@
    while [ "$minor" -le @PYTHON_MAX_SUPPORTED_MINOR@ ]; do
        link="/opt/send-to-influx/venv/lib/python3.${minor}"
        [ -L "$link" ] || rm -rf "$link"
        ln -sfn python3 "$link"
        minor=$((minor + 1))
    done
fi

if ! getent passwd send-to-influx >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    adduser --system --group --no-create-home --shell /usr/sbin/nologin send-to-influx
fi

# /opt/send-to-influx (the code) deliberately stays root-owned, exactly as
# dpkg unpacked it: the service only needs read/execute access (the venv is
# world-readable by default), and a service user that can write its own code
# turns any service compromise into persistent arbitrary-code execution. (An
# earlier version chown -R'ed the whole tree to send-to-influx on every
# configure, for no operational benefit.)

# settings.yaml is deliberately NOT a dpkg conffile (see build-deb.sh for the
# full reasoning: this script and send-to-influx-set-credential write into it,
# which dpkg's conffile machinery would flag as a local modification and prompt
# about on every upgrade that ships a changed example). Instead the example
# ships under /usr/share/send-to-influx and is copied into place only if
# missing, so an upgrade never touches an existing file - nor any
# permissions/ownership an admin has since changed for their own reasons.
# 644 (not 600) is safe as the initial default: send-to-influx never writes a
# real secret into this file, only placeholder text or (once systemd-creds is
# used) a cosmetic sentinel - see enforce_permissions in example_settings.yaml
# and SECURITY.md.
mkdir -p /etc/send-to-influx
if [ ! -e /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml ]; then
    cp /usr/share/send-to-influx/example_settings.yaml /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml
    chown send-to-influx:send-to-influx /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml
    chmod 644 /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml
fi

mkdir -p /etc/send-to-influx/credstore.encrypted
chmod 700 /etc/send-to-influx/credstore.encrypted
chown root:root /etc/send-to-influx/credstore.encrypted

# --- debconf-driven configuration -------------------------------------------
# Reads back whatever was answered in packaging/deb/config and acts on it via
# send-to-influx-set-credential - the only place any of this touches the
# filesystem (config itself is side-effect-free, a hard Debian packaging
# convention: dpkg-reconfigure/backing out of an install must never leave
# partial changes). See CLAUDE.md's "Credential storage (systemd-creds)" >
# "debconf-driven install" section for the design.
#
# Only applied on a genuinely fresh install or an explicit dpkg-reconfigure -
# never on a plain upgrade. Debconf's database persists every non-password
# answer indefinitely once given (it's a UI cache, not a change log), so
# "read back the database and act on it" is only meaningful on a run where
# the questions were actually (re)asked. Without this gate, every upgrade
# re-applied stale answers: sources-to-configure persists, so each
# previously-selected source was re-processed with its password answers long
# since cleared - a false "not fully configured - not enabling it" warning
# per source, on every upgrade - and Open-Meteo (no password field) silently
# re-wrote latitude/longitude into settings.yaml with the original install's
# answers, reverting any hand edits made since. dpkg-reconfigure exports
# DEBCONF_RECONFIGURE=1 specifically so postinst can tell it apart from a
# plain upgrade ($1/$2 are "configure <version>" for both); config carries
# the matching gate on the asking side, so a plain upgrade neither asks nor
# applies anything.
if [ -z "$2" ] || [ "${DEBCONF_RECONFIGURE:-}" = "1" ]; then
    . /usr/share/debconf/confmodule

    CLI=/usr/sbin/send-to-influx-set-credential
    CLI_FAILED=0
    # Secret prompts always come back blank on a reconfigure (debconf never
    # redisplays a password answer, and postinst clears the stored values
    # anyway - see below), with blank meaning "keep the previously stored
    # value". So everywhere below that requires a secret, a credential
    # already migrated into systemd-creds satisfies the requirement just as
    # well as a freshly-typed answer - otherwise every reconfigure of an
    # already-configured install would wrongly report its sources "not fully
    # configured" and skip auto-enable, purely because the admin (correctly)
    # left the secret prompts blank.
    CREDSTORE=/etc/send-to-influx/credstore.encrypted

    # $1 = credential name, $2 = value. Failure is recorded in $CLI_FAILED rather
    # than aborting (this whole flow is best-effort - a systemd-creds problem must
    # not block the rest of the package install).
    set_secret() {
        if ! printf '%s' "$2" | "$CLI" "$1" >/dev/null; then
            CLI_FAILED=1
            echo "send-to-influx: could not store credential '$1' - run 'sudo $CLI $1' by hand to finish, or (e.g. on systemd < 250, where systemd-creds is unavailable) put the value in /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml instead." >&2
        fi
    }

    # $1 = section name. Back-fills a top-level settings.yaml section from the
    # shipped example when it's missing. Needed because settings.yaml is written
    # once at install time and never rewritten by an upgrade (deliberate - see
    # build-deb.sh), so any section added by a LATER release is absent for exactly
    # the installs that have been running longest. Without this, --set-field fails
    # ("no 'mqtt:' section found") and, worse, enabling a source whose block is new
    # makes load_settings() raise a fatal ConfigError - which stops the whole
    # service, taking every already-working source down with it.
    ensure_section() {
        if ! "$CLI" --ensure-section "$1" >/dev/null; then
            CLI_FAILED=1
            echo "send-to-influx: could not add the '$1:' section to /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml - copy it from /usr/share/send-to-influx/example_settings.yaml by hand." >&2
        fi
    }

    # $1 = dotted.path, $2 = value. Same best-effort contract as set_secret.
    set_field() {
        if ! "$CLI" --set-field "$1" "$2" >/dev/null; then
            CLI_FAILED=1
            echo "send-to-influx: could not write '$1' to settings.yaml - edit it by hand." >&2
        fi
    }

    db_get send-to-influx/sources-to-configure
    SOURCES_RAW="$RET"
    # Normalise debconf's multiselect answer (comma-separated, with or without a
    # following space depending on frontend) so a simple substring match works.
    SOURCES=" $(echo "$SOURCES_RAW" | tr ',' ' ') "

    # --- InfluxDB connection - unconditional, regardless of source selection.
    # Leaving influx-url blank defaults to a local instance; identity/secret are
    # always applied regardless - even a bare local InfluxDB v2 needs a token.
    db_get send-to-influx/influx-url
    INFLUX_URL_RAW="$RET"
    INFLUX_URL="$INFLUX_URL_RAW"
    if [ -z "$INFLUX_URL" ]; then
        INFLUX_URL="http://localhost:8086"
    fi
    db_get send-to-influx/influx-identity
    INFLUX_IDENTITY="$RET"
    db_get send-to-influx/influx-secret
    INFLUX_SECRET="$RET"
    # Type: password answers are written to debconf's own database (a separate
    # passwords.dat store, chmod 600) - debconf-devel(7) advises clearing a
    # password value out of it "as soon as is possible" once consumed, and its
    # suggested way to do that is setting the value to the empty string: the
    # stored copy is gone, but the question stays registered with its seen
    # flag intact. (An earlier version used db_unregister here, which also
    # cleared the value - but deleting the question deletes its seen flag with
    # it, and the question was recreated fresh/unseen from the templates file
    # on the next run, so debconf re-asked it, blank, on every upgrade.)
    # Cleared here, right after reading, regardless of what happens with the
    # value from here on.
    db_set send-to-influx/influx-secret "" || true
    # influx-identity is cleared too, even though it's Type: string: for a v1
    # install it's the InfluxDB *username*, which everywhere else is treated
    # as a credential (encrypted into systemd-creds as influx-user) - leaving
    # it in debconf's regular, more widely readable database indefinitely
    # would be internally inconsistent. Like the secrets, it's re-collected
    # fresh on a reconfigure, where blank means "keep what's configured".
    db_set send-to-influx/influx-identity "" || true

    INFLUX_OK=0
    if [ -n "$INFLUX_IDENTITY" ] && [ -n "$INFLUX_SECRET" ]; then
        INFLUX_VERSION="$("$CLI" --detect-influx-version "$INFLUX_URL" 2>/dev/null || echo unknown)"
        if [ "$INFLUX_VERSION" = "v2" ]; then
            # example_settings.yaml ships influx.org/influx.token as real, empty
            # keys (alongside the v1 user/password placeholders) specifically so
            # set_field/set_secret below have something to rewrite on a fresh
            # install - an empty token is falsy, so it doesn't make is_v2 = bool(
            # token) misfire for a v1-only install that never touches these
            # fields. Only attempt set_secret influx-token if set_field succeeded
            # first, defense-in-depth against a hand-edited settings.yaml that's
            # since had these keys removed - otherwise the token would end up
            # encrypted into systemd-creds with the drop-in already referencing
            # it, while settings.yaml has no influx.token key left to point back
            # at it: a partially migrated, inconsistent state, worse than just
            # failing cleanly.
            set_field influx.url "$INFLUX_URL"
            set_field influx.org "$INFLUX_IDENTITY"
            if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                set_secret influx-token "$INFLUX_SECRET"
            fi
            if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                INFLUX_OK=1
            fi
        elif [ "$INFLUX_VERSION" = "v1" ]; then
            # Same defence as the v2 branch above: only migrate the secrets
            # into systemd-creds if the settings.yaml write succeeded first,
            # so a hand-mangled settings.yaml can't end up with credentials
            # encrypted (and the drop-in referencing them) while the file has
            # no influx block pointing back at them.
            set_field influx.url "$INFLUX_URL"
            if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                set_secret influx-user "$INFLUX_IDENTITY"
                set_secret influx-password "$INFLUX_SECRET"
            fi
            if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                INFLUX_OK=1
            fi
        else
            echo "send-to-influx: could not detect the InfluxDB version at $INFLUX_URL (unreachable?) - run 'sudo dpkg-reconfigure send-to-influx' once it's reachable." >&2
        fi
    elif [ -e "$CREDSTORE/influx-token.cred" ] || { [ -e "$CREDSTORE/influx-user.cred" ] && [ -e "$CREDSTORE/influx-password.cred" ]; }; then
        # Blank secret with InfluxDB credentials already stored in
        # systemd-creds: keep them, count InfluxDB as configured so
        # newly-selected sources below can still auto-enable
        # (--ensure-influx-storage resolves the stored credentials itself),
        # and still apply any *non-secret* connection details actually
        # provided this run - a changed URL or user/org on a reconfigure must
        # not be silently dropped just because the secret prompt was
        # (correctly) left blank. Which field the identity belongs to is
        # inferred from which credential exists rather than re-running URL
        # detection: a stored token means v2 (identity = org, a plain field),
        # stored user+password means v1 (identity = username, itself kept in
        # systemd-creds). Blank means "keep" for every field here, matching
        # the secret's own semantics - notably a blank URL is NOT rewritten
        # to the localhost default, since this branch is also reached by
        # installs whose custom influx.url was only ever hand-edited into
        # settings.yaml and never answered via debconf.
        CLI_FAILED=0
        if [ -n "$INFLUX_URL_RAW" ]; then
            set_field influx.url "$INFLUX_URL_RAW"
        fi
        if [ -n "$INFLUX_IDENTITY" ]; then
            if [ -e "$CREDSTORE/influx-token.cred" ]; then
                set_field influx.org "$INFLUX_IDENTITY"
            else
                set_secret influx-user "$INFLUX_IDENTITY"
            fi
        fi
        # A secret typed with the identity left blank is a rotation of the
        # stored credential (the common "new token, same org" case) - route
        # it the same way instead of silently dropping it.
        if [ -n "$INFLUX_SECRET" ]; then
            if [ -e "$CREDSTORE/influx-token.cred" ]; then
                set_secret influx-token "$INFLUX_SECRET"
            else
                set_secret influx-password "$INFLUX_SECRET"
            fi
        fi
        if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
            INFLUX_OK=1
        fi
    else
        # Only warn if the admin actually engaged with the prompts this run -
        # selected a source (which needs InfluxDB to do anything useful) or
        # entered a secret without the matching identity. A run where
        # everything was left blank (e.g. a non-interactive install) stays
        # silent.
        if [ -n "$SOURCES_RAW" ] || [ -n "$INFLUX_SECRET" ]; then
            echo "send-to-influx: InfluxDB user/org or password/token not provided - skipping InfluxDB setup and any source auto-enable this run." >&2
        fi
    fi

    # --- Hue ---
    HUE_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in
        *" hue "*)
            db_get send-to-influx/hue-host
            HUE_HOST="$RET"
            db_get send-to-influx/hue-user
            HUE_USER="$RET"
            # Clear the consumed password (see influx-secret above).
            db_set send-to-influx/hue-user "" || true
            if [ -n "$HUE_HOST" ] && { [ -n "$HUE_USER" ] || [ -e "$CREDSTORE/hue-user.cred" ]; }; then
                CLI_FAILED=0
                set_field hue.host "$HUE_HOST"
                if [ -n "$HUE_USER" ]; then
                    set_secret hue-user "$HUE_USER"
                fi
                db_get send-to-influx/hue-temperature-units
                if [ -n "$RET" ]; then
                    set_field hue.temperature_units "$RET"
                fi
                if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                    HUE_OK=1
                fi
            else
                echo "send-to-influx: Hue not fully configured (host/user missing) - not enabling it." >&2
            fi
            ;;
    esac

    # --- MyEnergi (apikey shared across zappi/harvi/eddi - asked/applied once) ---
    # MYENERGI_OK=1 means the API key is available: freshly entered and
    # successfully stored, or already sitting in systemd-creds from before.
    MYENERGI_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in
        *" zappi "*|*" harvi "*|*" eddi "*)
            db_get send-to-influx/myenergi-apikey
            MYENERGI_APIKEY="$RET"
            # Clear the consumed password (see influx-secret above).
            db_set send-to-influx/myenergi-apikey "" || true
            if [ -n "$MYENERGI_APIKEY" ]; then
                CLI_FAILED=0
                set_secret myenergi-apikey "$MYENERGI_APIKEY"
                if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                    MYENERGI_OK=1
                fi
            elif [ -e "$CREDSTORE/myenergi-apikey.cred" ]; then
                MYENERGI_OK=1
            fi
            ;;
    esac

    ZAPPI_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in
        *" zappi "*)
            db_get send-to-influx/zappi-serial
            ZAPPI_SERIAL="$RET"
            if [ "$MYENERGI_OK" = 1 ] && [ -n "$ZAPPI_SERIAL" ]; then
                CLI_FAILED=0
                set_field zappi.serial "$ZAPPI_SERIAL"
                if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                    ZAPPI_OK=1
                fi
            else
                echo "send-to-influx: Zappi not fully configured (MyEnergi API key/serial missing) - not enabling it." >&2
            fi
            ;;
    esac

    HARVI_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in
        *" harvi "*)
            db_get send-to-influx/harvi-serial
            HARVI_SERIAL="$RET"
            if [ "$MYENERGI_OK" = 1 ] && [ -n "$HARVI_SERIAL" ]; then
                CLI_FAILED=0
                set_field harvi.serial "$HARVI_SERIAL"
                if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                    HARVI_OK=1
                fi
            else
                echo "send-to-influx: Harvi not fully configured (MyEnergi API key/serial missing) - not enabling it." >&2
            fi
            ;;
    esac

    EDDI_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in
        *" eddi "*)
            db_get send-to-influx/eddi-serial
            EDDI_SERIAL="$RET"
            if [ "$MYENERGI_OK" = 1 ] && [ -n "$EDDI_SERIAL" ]; then
                CLI_FAILED=0
                set_field eddi.serial "$EDDI_SERIAL"
                if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                    EDDI_OK=1
                fi
            else
                echo "send-to-influx: Eddi not fully configured (MyEnergi API key/serial missing) - not enabling it." >&2
            fi
            ;;
    esac

    # --- Octopus ---
    OCTOPUS_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in
        *" octopus "*)
            db_get send-to-influx/octopus-api-key
            OCTOPUS_KEY="$RET"
            # Clear the consumed password (see influx-secret above).
            db_set send-to-influx/octopus-api-key "" || true
            db_get send-to-influx/octopus-mpan
            OCTOPUS_MPAN="$RET"
            db_get send-to-influx/octopus-meter-serial
            OCTOPUS_METER="$RET"
            if { [ -n "$OCTOPUS_KEY" ] || [ -e "$CREDSTORE/octopus-api-key.cred" ]; } && [ -n "$OCTOPUS_MPAN" ] && [ -n "$OCTOPUS_METER" ]; then
                CLI_FAILED=0
                if [ -n "$OCTOPUS_KEY" ]; then
                    set_secret octopus-api-key "$OCTOPUS_KEY"
                fi
                set_field octopus.mpan "$OCTOPUS_MPAN"
                set_field octopus.meter_serial "$OCTOPUS_METER"
                if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                    OCTOPUS_OK=1
                fi
            else
                echo "send-to-influx: Octopus not fully configured (API key/MPAN/meter serial missing) - not enabling it." >&2
            fi
            ;;
    esac

    # --- Open-Meteo ---
    OPENMETEO_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in
        *" openmeteo "*)
            db_get send-to-influx/openmeteo-latitude
            OM_LAT="$RET"
            db_get send-to-influx/openmeteo-longitude
            OM_LON="$RET"
            if [ -n "$OM_LAT" ] && [ -n "$OM_LON" ]; then
                CLI_FAILED=0
                set_field openmeteo.latitude "$OM_LAT"
                set_field openmeteo.longitude "$OM_LON"
                if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                    OPENMETEO_OK=1
                fi
            else
                echo "send-to-influx: Open-Meteo not fully configured (latitude/longitude missing) - not enabling it." >&2
            fi
            ;;
    esac

    # --- Nuki (shared MQTT broker block) ---
    # The second shared-infrastructure block after InfluxDB, but conditional:
    # only processed when an MQTT-based source was selected, mirroring config's
    # gating on the asking side. Only the broker host is required (see
    # below); username/password are optional - blank means anonymous broker
    # access, a completely valid configuration. Whatever auth *was* provided
    # is applied, and a blank password with an mqtt-password already in
    # systemd-creds keeps that stored credential (see influx-secret).
    NUKI_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in
        *" nuki "*)
            db_get send-to-influx/mqtt-broker-host
            MQTT_HOST="$RET"
            db_get send-to-influx/mqtt-username
            MQTT_USER="$RET"
            db_get send-to-influx/mqtt-password
            MQTT_PASS="$RET"
            # Clear the consumed password (see influx-secret above); the
            # username is cleared too, like influx-identity - it's the other
            # half of a credential pair.
            db_set send-to-influx/mqtt-password "" || true
            db_set send-to-influx/mqtt-username "" || true
            # A non-empty broker host is required (hue-host style, not
            # blank-keeps: debconf *string* answers persist across
            # reconfigures, so any install configured through these prompts
            # always has a non-blank host here - a blank one means the host
            # was only ever hand-edited or never set, where auto-enabling
            # would be speculative, possibly against the shipped placeholder).
            # Auth is optional but must be coherent: both blank means
            # anonymous access, both supplied means authenticated - a username
            # with no password material is neither (see the elif).
            if [ -z "$MQTT_HOST" ]; then
                echo "send-to-influx: Nuki not fully configured (MQTT broker host missing) - not enabling it." >&2
            elif [ -n "$MQTT_USER" ] && [ -z "$MQTT_PASS" ] && [ ! -e "$CREDSTORE/mqtt-password.cred" ]; then
                # Incoherent auth: a username with no password material would
                # auto-enable straight into an authenticated connect with an
                # empty password - a guaranteed rejection retry loop. Both for
                # authenticated access, neither for anonymous.
                echo "send-to-influx: Nuki not fully configured (username given without a password - provide both for authenticated access, or neither for anonymous) - not enabling it." >&2
            else
                CLI_FAILED=0
                # Both sections may be absent on an install that predates them.
                # nuki's own block matters as much as mqtt's: --enable-source below
                # would otherwise add nuki to sources: with no nuki: section for it,
                # which fails validation fatally at next start.
                ensure_section mqtt
                ensure_section nuki
                set_field mqtt.broker_host "$MQTT_HOST"
                if [ -n "$MQTT_USER" ]; then
                    set_field mqtt.username "$MQTT_USER"
                fi
                if [ -n "$MQTT_PASS" ]; then
                    set_secret mqtt-password "$MQTT_PASS"
                fi
                if [ "$CLI_FAILED" = 0 ]; then
                    NUKI_OK=1
                fi
            fi
            ;;
    esac

    # --- CarbonIntensity / Speedtest: nothing beyond selection is required ---
    CARBONINTENSITY_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in *" carbonintensity "*) CARBONINTENSITY_OK=1 ;; esac
    SPEEDTEST_OK=0
    case "$SOURCES" in *" speedtest "*) SPEEDTEST_OK=1 ;; esac

    # --- Remote MCP server ---
    # The third shared-infrastructure block, gated on its own mcp-enable boolean
    # rather than a source selection: the MCP server is an optional interface over
    # every source, not a source itself. Independent of INFLUX_OK too - the server
    # runs regardless (queries just fail if InfluxDB is unreachable), so it's not
    # inside the auto-enable/INFLUX_OK block below. The service is only (re)started
    # at the very END of this script, so only the FINAL settings.yaml state matters
    # - which is what makes the enable-then-revert on a password failure safe.
    db_get send-to-influx/mcp-enable
    if [ "$RET" = "true" ]; then
        db_get send-to-influx/mcp-public-url
        MCP_URL="$RET"
        db_get send-to-influx/mcp-user
        MCP_USER="$RET"
        db_get send-to-influx/mcp-password
        MCP_PASS="$RET"
        # Clear only the consumed *secret*. mcp-user is a non-secret string, and -
        # unlike mqtt-username (optional, blank=anonymous) - it is *required*: it
        # must persist and pre-fill on the next reconfigure, exactly like hue-host
        # and mqtt-broker-host, so leave it in debconf's database (see the
        # required-field templates). Clearing it here was the bug that made it
        # blank on reconfigure and blocked password-only rotation.
        db_set send-to-influx/mcp-password "" || true
        # Was a credential already stored before this run? If so this is a
        # reconfigure of an already-enabled install, which changes the failure
        # handling below (never disable a working install).
        MCP_CRED_EXISTED=0
        [ -e "$CREDSTORE/mcp-password.cred" ] && MCP_CRED_EXISTED=1
        # An enabled mcp block needs public_url AND a coherent user+password, or
        # load_settings() raises a fatal ConfigError that stops the WHOLE service
        # (every collector), not just the MCP server. All three are required
        # (public_url/user pre-fill on reconfigure; password may be freshly typed
        # or already in systemd-creds). If any is missing, leave settings.yaml
        # untouched - which keeps a hand-configured install working and a shipped
        # blank block disabled, without ever writing an incoherent partial block.
        if [ -z "$MCP_URL" ] || [ -z "$MCP_USER" ]; then
            echo "send-to-influx: MCP server not fully configured (public URL and username required) - leaving its configuration unchanged." >&2
        elif [ -z "$MCP_PASS" ] && [ "$MCP_CRED_EXISTED" = 0 ]; then
            echo "send-to-influx: MCP server not fully configured (login password required) - leaving its configuration unchanged." >&2
        else
            ensure_section mcp
            set_field mcp.public_url "$MCP_URL"
            set_field mcp.user "$MCP_USER"
            if [ -n "$MCP_PASS" ]; then
                if ! printf '%s' "$MCP_PASS" | "$CLI" mcp-password >/dev/null; then
                    CLI_FAILED=1
                    if [ "$MCP_CRED_EXISTED" = 1 ]; then
                        # A password was already stored: the previously-working
                        # credential is still in place, so the block stays coherent
                        # and enabled. Only the *new* password wasn't stored.
                        echo "send-to-influx: could not store the new MCP login password - keeping the previously stored one. Retry with 'sudo $CLI mcp-password'." >&2
                    else
                        # Fresh enable with no prior credential: user+public_url got
                        # written but the password didn't, which is
                        # user-without-password - a fatal validation error that
                        # takes every collector down. Revert the username so the
                        # FINAL block is coherent-and-disabled. Only the
                        # end-of-script state matters (the service restarts once, at
                        # the end), so this transient write-then-revert is safe.
                        # Use the set_field helper (not a raw '|| true') so a
                        # failure to revert is itself tracked and reported rather
                        # than silently leaving the fatal user-without-password.
                        set_field mcp.user ""
                        echo "send-to-influx: could not store the MCP login password - MCP server disabled (username reverted). Set it by hand with 'sudo $CLI mcp-password', then re-run 'dpkg-reconfigure send-to-influx'." >&2
                    fi
                fi
            fi
        fi
    fi

    # Belt-and-braces: clear every credential-bearing answer - the five
    # password-type questions plus the two string-typed identity halves
    # (influx-identity, a possible v1 username, and mqtt-username - see the
    # notes where each is first cleared above) - whether or not its source
    # was selected. The per-source blocks above
    # only read-and-clear a secret when its source was actually selected -
    # but a preseed (debconf-set-selections) can supply e.g. hue-user without
    # ticking hue, and that answer would otherwise sit in passwords.dat
    # indefinitely. Re-clearing the already-cleared ones is harmless.
    for q in influx-secret influx-identity hue-user myenergi-apikey octopus-api-key mqtt-password mqtt-username mcp-password; do
        db_set "send-to-influx/$q" "" || true
    done

    # --- Auto-enable: only sources that were selected AND had every required
    # field supplied AND a working InfluxDB block get their database/bucket
    # created (best-effort - logged, not fatal, on failure) and added to
    # sources: in settings.yaml. Anything not fully satisfied is left exactly
    # as opt-in as it is today, with a message explaining what's missing.
    if [ "$INFLUX_OK" = 1 ]; then
        if [ "$HUE_OK" = 1 ]; then
            "$CLI" --ensure-influx-storage hue_db || true
            "$CLI" --enable-source hue || true
        fi
        if [ "$ZAPPI_OK" = 1 ]; then
            "$CLI" --ensure-influx-storage zappi_db || true
            "$CLI" --enable-source zappi || true
        fi
        if [ "$HARVI_OK" = 1 ]; then
            "$CLI" --ensure-influx-storage myenergi_db || true
            "$CLI" --enable-source harvi || true
        fi
        if [ "$EDDI_OK" = 1 ]; then
            "$CLI" --ensure-influx-storage myenergi_db || true
            "$CLI" --enable-source eddi || true
        fi
        if [ "$OCTOPUS_OK" = 1 ]; then
            "$CLI" --ensure-influx-storage octopus_db || true
            "$CLI" --enable-source octopus || true
        fi
        if [ "$OPENMETEO_OK" = 1 ]; then
            "$CLI" --ensure-influx-storage weather_db || true
            "$CLI" --enable-source openmeteo || true
        fi
        if [ "$CARBONINTENSITY_OK" = 1 ]; then
            "$CLI" --ensure-influx-storage grid_db || true
            "$CLI" --enable-source carbonintensity || true
        fi
        if [ "$SPEEDTEST_OK" = 1 ]; then
            "$CLI" --ensure-influx-storage speedtest_db || true
            "$CLI" --enable-source speedtest || true
        fi
        if [ "$NUKI_OK" = 1 ]; then
            "$CLI" --ensure-influx-storage nuki_db || true
            "$CLI" --enable-source nuki || true
        fi
    fi

    # No further db_* calls below - let the frontend go so the rest of the
    # script's output lands directly on the terminal.
    db_stop || true
fi

WAS_ACTIVE=0
RESTARTED=0
if [ -d /run/systemd/system ]; then
    systemctl daemon-reload || true

    # Reload rsyslog so a newly-dropped-in or changed
    # /etc/rsyslog.d/49-send-to-influx.conf takes effect now rather than
    # needing a manual step or reboot. try-restart (not restart) is a no-op
    # if rsyslog isn't currently running, so this can't start a service the
    # operator has deliberately left stopped or never installed (rsyslog is a
    # Recommends:, not a Depends: - the app logs to stdout/journald either
    # way, this is purely about the optional dedicated-logfile split). Run on
    # every configure, not gated on fresh-install/reconfigure like the
    # debconf-driven settings.yaml block above: the file's *content* can
    # legitimately change between package versions, unlike settings.yaml
    # which is deliberately never rewritten by an upgrade.
    systemctl try-restart rsyslog 2>/dev/null || true

    # On an upgrade (or a dpkg-reconfigure that just rewrote configuration),
    # restart the service if - and only if - it's currently running: dpkg has
    # already replaced the code under /opt/send-to-influx, but the running
    # process keeps executing the old version until restarted, and upgrades
    # are commonly unattended (cron/apt timers), so a "please restart" hint
    # in the output would never be seen - even on an attended run, nobody
    # reads every line of every upgraded package's output. "enabled" doesn't
    # imply "running" (could be enabled-but-stopped, or running-but-disabled),
    # so check the actual current state; a stopped service is left exactly as
    # it is - this never *starts* anything. Guarded on /run/systemd/system
    # like the daemon-reload above: on a non-systemd host systemctl may not
    # exist at all.
    if systemctl is-active --quiet send-to-influx 2>/dev/null; then
        WAS_ACTIVE=1
        if [ -n "$2" ]; then
            if systemctl restart send-to-influx; then
                RESTARTED=1
            else
                echo "send-to-influx: automatic restart after upgrade failed - the service may still be running the previous version. Check 'systemctl status send-to-influx'." >&2
            fi
        fi
    fi
fi

# Fresh installs get the full "here's what to do next" message; upgrades get
# a short factual note instead - "configure" receives the previously-
# configured version as $2, empty only on a genuinely fresh install. A
# dpkg-reconfigure run (also "configure" with $2 set) skips the upgrade
# message: the admin just ran a deliberate, interactive command and needs no
# guidance about an upgrade that didn't happen - the restart above still
# applies so their new answers take effect, noted with a single line.
#
# ($1 is guaranteed to be "configure" this far down - every other action
# no-ops at the top of the script - so $2 reliably means "previously-
# configured version, empty only on a fresh install" here.)
if [ "${DEBCONF_RECONFIGURE:-}" = "1" ] && [ -n "$2" ]; then
    if [ "$RESTARTED" = 1 ]; then
        echo "send-to-influx: service restarted to apply the new configuration."
    fi
else
    if [ -z "$2" ]; then
        cat <<'MSG'

send-to-influx installed. Before starting the service:

  1. Edit /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml with your device and InfluxDB details.
     (Copied from example_settings.yaml - it will not work as-is. If you answered
     the install prompts, some sources may already be fully configured and enabled.)
  2. Optionally store secrets in systemd-creds instead of plaintext (requires systemd >= 250):
       sudo send-to-influx-set-credential <name>
     Run 'sudo send-to-influx-set-credential --list' to see the available credential names.
     Run 'sudo dpkg-reconfigure send-to-influx' to revisit the install prompts.
  3. Enable and start the service:
       systemctl enable --now send-to-influx

The service is not started automatically since it needs configuration first.

MSG
    else
        if [ "$RESTARTED" = 1 ]; then
            cat <<'MSG'

send-to-influx upgraded; the service was running, so it has been restarted
and is now running the new version. Your /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml
and any systemd-creds credentials are untouched - upgrades never modify
them. Run 'sudo dpkg-reconfigure send-to-influx' at any time to revisit the
interactive setup (including migrating secrets into systemd-creds).

MSG
        elif [ "$WAS_ACTIVE" = 1 ]; then
            # The restart failure warning has already gone to stderr above -
            # repeat the essential fact here so it's also in the normal flow
            # of the final status output.
            cat <<'MSG'

send-to-influx upgraded, but restarting the running service failed - it is
likely still running the PREVIOUS version. Check
'systemctl status send-to-influx' and restart it by hand. Your configuration
is untouched.

MSG
        else
            cat <<'MSG'

send-to-influx upgraded. The service was not running, so it has not been
started - it's left exactly as it was. Your /etc/send-to-influx/settings.yaml
and any systemd-creds credentials are untouched. Run
'sudo dpkg-reconfigure send-to-influx' at any time to revisit the interactive
setup (including migrating secrets into systemd-creds).

MSG
        fi
    fi
fi

exit 0
